### Issue #11: React hooks called conditionally (Rules of Hooks violation)

**What's happening:** In [Admin.jsx](file:///d:/CODING/prompter/src/pages/Admin.jsx#L25-L29), [Landing.jsx](file:///d:/CODING/prompter/src/pages/Landing.jsx#L27-L31), and [Profile.jsx](file:///d:/CODING/prompter/src/pages/Profile.jsx#L22-L26), there's an early return *before* hooks are called:

```jsx
// Admin.jsx
if (isLoadingAuth) {
  return <div />; // ← EARLY RETURN HERE
}
const { canShareVault } = usePlan(); // ← HOOK AFTER EARLY RETURN
const [search, setSearch] = useState(''); // ← MORE HOOKS
```

**Why it's a problem:** This violates React's Rules of Hooks. React requires hooks to be called in the exact same order on every render. An early return before hooks means they're conditionally skipped. React will throw errors or silently break in production. This is a live bug that you haven't hit yet by luck.

**Severity:** 🔴 **HIGH — ticking time bomb**

**Fix:** Move ALL hooks to the top of the component, BEFORE any conditional returns:
```jsx
export default function Admin() {
  const { user, isAuthenticated, isLoadingAuth } = useAuth();
  const { canShareVault, planInfo } = usePlan(); // ← BEFORE early return
  const [search, setSearch] = useState('');       // ← BEFORE early return
  // ... all other hooks

  if (isLoadingAuth) return <div />;
  // ... rest of component
}
```

